I’d suggest trying to freeform your arrangements in real time. Put everything on an endless loop, hit record and mute parts in real time to build each different section. If you do t have enough diversity in parts when doing that, it means you need to add more tracks to your loop.

Don’t get hung up on the style you are going for, just focus on getting to some kind of end result, you can adjust the styling of it later.

>>114464997
desu you really have to know how to play the drums to program drums that sound real.

But If you just want less robotic sounding, it’s all about syncopation. Syncopation makes the rhythm. You can have the most robotic on-the-grid kick, snare and hats, but when you add another perc sound that accents an off beat in one of the measures, it fixes it and sounds human. The breakbeat sample on top works because it has syncopation in the pattern.

And to preemptively clarify what I mean by accenting the off beats. It’s the extra kick drum hits just before the end of the phrase. It’s the extra snare hit before or after the 2s and 4s. It’s the Tom hit when every other perc is on a rest.

Good tune btw

My take on the matter:
I just did some heavy leads tone test on top of this Youtube heavy track https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=UTPADCjSIcE

No mixing or processing involved, just pure sound of ZOOM DSP into CAB sims in DAW. It cuts right through the track. This unit is a digital signal processor, but it has a analog valve single tube for preamp stage for some gain saturation.

https://vocaroo.com/1aoJxs7V9i7N

Even though this unit is 30 years old, it is still better in "cutting through" any heavy distorted mix than even some of the NEURAL DSP sim stuff I have tried that use pure guitar signal without any analog stages before the DAW. And this is without any post-EQ or mixing.

Literally just get some old hardware, these units sell for about 100-120 dollars used, the avg. you would spend on some shitty Amp sim with 1000 features and they all sound mediocre and always require shit ton of mixing, EQ and fucking around. Everything else, IRs, Power Amp sims, can be found for free.

>>114466377
>Why does so much avant-prog sound so angular and "chunky"?
Disregard the idiotic answers you've received so far. It has to do with the level of conceptuality. Typical progressive rock albums tend to be conceptual on the album level, e.g. Eloy's Power and the Passion, which is about a protagonist going through time travel, finding love, and so on... We call that a "concept album". Meanwhile, "avant-prog" does that individually, on the track level, (usually) without an overarching theme or plot for the whole album.

It definitely requires more attention (at first) from the listener, since each track typically has to say something different. This obviously gives the impression of "chunkiness", a lack of "smooth transitioning" between the tracks, and a sense of lack of "transitionality" from track to track.

I personally like to think of it as the level of abstraction being higher, and I appreciate an "avant-prog" album's attempt of synchronizing the individual tracks with the overarching album theme, but some of my favorite ones do not even attempt to do that.

I just did some heavy leads tone test on top of this Youtube heavy track https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=UTPADCjSIcE

No mixing or processing involved, just pure sound of ZOOM DSP into CAB sims in DAW. It cuts right through the track and mix. This unit is a digital signal processor, but it has a analog valve single tube for preamp stage for some gain saturation.

https://vocaroo.com/1aoJxs7V9i7N

Even though this unit is 30 years old, it is still better in "cutting through" any heavy distorted mix than even some of the NEURAL DSP sim stuff I have tried that use pure guitar signal without any analog stages before the DAW. And this is without any post-EQ or mixing. Literally just get some old hardware, these units sell for about 100-120 dollars used, the avg. you would spend on some shitty Amp sim with 1000 features and they all sound mediocre and always require shit ton of mixing, EQ and fucking around. Everything else, IRs, Power Amp sims, can be found for free.

I've hoarded certain gear that is still affordable (old rack preamps) because I've noticed that they go on sale less often (Ebay, Reverb) and when they do: someone has added like $100-200 to the price and other sellers follow the lead. In 5 years it will have like $700 added to avg. sell price. Decided few years ago that better to buy 5 units of the same thing for $500 than pay $2500 for it 5 years down the road. This stuff is mainly used for my bread and butter setup recording and the other units are literally for me just in case some of these breaks and they are sealed/stored away carefully. Maybe it's hoarder logic, but I calculated that if one unit on average lasts me ~15 years without breaking and I have spare parts these should last me a lifetime and 20 years from now who the fuck knows how absurd the prices of used market is when some of these 80s-90s units will be 50-60 years old.

posts.com:
hey guys I started playing guitar recently, just been learning some songs for about 30-45 minutes a day, maybe an hour total. I'm a complete beginner, does anyone have some resources to keep me progressing at a good rate?

Or should I just keep learning songs until I can move my fret hand around well before I get into memorizing chords and scales? Im still muting notes and not playing smoothly at all, especially transitioning between wildly different phrases

posts.name: Anonymous
posts.com:
>>114472786
The most efficient way would be sticking to a curriculum either something made by someone online (tons of youtube channels have series for free), paying for a tutor that will give you a plan of attack and correct poor technique or getting a good course book. Then learning songs on top of that after you do your daily homework. Having a tutor or doing a video course can help a lot because you can follow their technique like hand/wrist rather than trying to figure out how to get to the next string yourself.

Only learning songs you want to play is a valid strategy if that's what keeps you motivated but you'll run into roadblocks more often and when you get a bit better it can be hard to find specific songs to practice specific techniques you need to work on. As long as you're playing the song very slowly to make sure you know it instead of trying to brute force playing it at full speed. So you need to find a balance between staying motivated by playing what you want while keeping pace on improving so you don't get frustrated and give up.

Ibanez's entry level guitars are very solid these days.
>I prefer the sound of acoustics though, so I'm unsure if I should go in that direction
Get an acoustic then, if you stick with it it'll make picking up electric later even easier since you're used to much heavier strings and you can't really hide poor technique on acoustic. Not sure what your budget is but the Epiphone J45 and Hummingbird are very very good acoustics if you can find one for less than $350, and the Yamaha (Yamaha FG800) and Ibanez (Ibanez AW54) entry level ones are very good too.

Good acoustics sometimes cost a little more than a good electric but you also don't need to buy an amp so it evens out. But I would recommend trying them out in a store to see what's comfortable if you can then you don't need to worry about things like adjusting the truss rod to start playing since a lot of them are shipped very slack.

look, I understand the flexiblity on more modern music, but calling "songs" to harpsichord works, concertos from the baroque era, or symphonies and sonatas from the classical and romantic era is just wrong. There is hypothetically a limit to the number of permutations that a set of notes can hold, if there is a limit to the number of total notes played. >>114454395
My violinist once described my music system as "being able to play chamber music with yourself."

The whole goal is really to use computers to do something in music never done before. I believe we've literally achieved new musical visions and concepts because we thoroughly deconstructed the improper use of PCs in music-making and built it back up again properly. No gay DAWs, no faggy synthesizers or sequencers. No MIDI bullshit. It's all just code - an LSTM trained on hundreds of hours of free improvisation from world-class instrumentalists. SuperCollider runs the show, using supernova and a couple sclang servers to do all the real-time sampling and live-mixing, Hypercore to store all the training data, and tensorflow chomps on the new data via a CUDA setup overnight after the performance is over.

We seed the data with the bitcoin spot price, local weather forecasts, and use sensors on the performers' body. We leave no stone unturned. My goal is to use today's weapons of war to propel musicians to even greater heights. Fuck electronic dance music. I want to live in a world where we were able to give Sun Ra the powers of AI.

The passage of time, a relentless and unyielding force, does not invoke within me a feeling of fear. Rather, it is the transient nature of existence, the fleeting and illusory perception of motion that consciousness imbues upon the world, that gives me pause. Ageing, though a natural and inevitable process, has never been a source of dread for me, as I have never harboured a desire to remain in a state of perpetual juvenility. Even death, though a universal and inescapable eventuality, does not fill me with terror, though I am not yet fully prepared to confront it.

What truly fills me with an abject sense of foreboding is the prospect of reaching a state of adult maturity, one in which I must toil ceaselessly each day in order to fulfil the demands of taxation, often providing funding for the nefarious endeavours of corrupt politicians, while also procuring the basic necessities of life for my domestic dwelling. I envision returning home, drained and haggard from the day's labours, flipping on the television to the last channel I viewed, a news outlet espousing a similar political ideology to my own, and becoming embittered by the distorted reality they propagate. I cook without enthusiasm, rueing the mistakes of my past and the missed opportunities that haunt me.

I find myself seated in a state of silent despondency, ruminating on how every plan I devise ends in failure or a mere scrawl on paper; how each year and each breath seem shorter and less ardent, and how each day brings me closer to the ultimate finality. It is this scenario that keeps me awake at night, overwhelmed by my errors and haunted by my missteps.

posts.com:
Patsy Cline: Live at the Cimarron Ballroom (MCA, 1997)
Cline's current iconicity (which for all I know could signal a heroic surge that will leave her as fixed a star as Aretha Franklin or Edith Piaf) is bound up in the vogue for pre/nonrock pop (which for all I know could prove permanent). Her Virginia twang mere seasoning in an unusually robust pop voice, she's Patti Page with guts. But the main reason she's remembered as the most credible of the countrypolitans is that countrypolitan was invented for her, by producer Owen Bradley. Entertaining the Southern folks who were her bread-and-butter--at maybe $500 a show, pickup backup provided--she was and remains something else. And this 1961 Tulsa gig with Leon McAuliffe's Cimarron Boys establish that the spare physicality and exquisite timing of her Grand Old Opry transcriptions are only a starting point. She could have used more rehearsal here. But the Western swing maestro led a band that was ready for anything, and Cline rose to their challenge as they did to hers: hard, high plains dance music, with her amazing trademark yowl at the end of "Lovesick Blues" a promise of the "Shake Rattle and Roll" she has all set to follow. A-

posts.com:
Jahseh was essentially a cloud martyr.

Everyone is claiming this was a random robbery, but it's clear what was actually happening: his killers were driven to take his life solely for the sake of cloud. They wanted infamy of their own and found it in gunning down a 20-year old.

As Jah was taking his final breath, he was surrounded by kids taking video and pictures of him. Why? For clout. No one was taking his pulse, no one was calling 911, everyone was standing around with their phones out as his body was clinging to life.

The moral lesson of Jahseh's life story should be a cautionary tale of the horrors of social media and how it's fucked our society beyond belief.

RIP Jah. See you in Heaven...
